00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:48.161 align:middle line:10%
>>MARIANNE WILLIAMSON: Thank
you so much for having me.

00:00:48.161 --> 00:00:50.680 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So why do we
have issues around money?

00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:51.350 align:middle line:90%
What is that?

00:00:51.350 --> 00:00:53.834 align:middle line:84%
Is it a social conversation,
a societal conversation?

00:00:53.834 --> 00:00:56.000 align:middle line:10%
>>WILLIAMSON: Well, obviously,
our material survival

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:57.160 align:middle line:10%
is important.

00:00:57.160 --> 00:00:58.730 align:middle line:10%
We need a home to live in.

00:00:58.730 --> 00:01:01.600 align:middle line:10%
We need to put money--
put food on the table,

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:03.540 align:middle line:10%
not only for ourselves
but for children.

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:05.710 align:middle line:10%
So we don't have to
apologize for the fact

00:01:05.710 --> 00:01:08.920 align:middle line:10%
that it's a topic that
everybody living in this world

00:01:08.920 --> 00:01:10.050 align:middle line:10%
has to deal with.

00:01:10.050 --> 00:01:12.820 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: But is it something
that we identify ourselves with?

00:01:12.820 --> 00:01:15.040 align:middle line:10%
I mean, do we identify our
self-worth and how much

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:17.255 align:middle line:10%
is that attached to our income?

00:01:17.255 --> 00:01:19.130 align:middle line:10%
>>WILLIAMSON: Well, I
think that certainly we

00:01:19.130 --> 00:01:21.880 align:middle line:10%
have financialized almost
everything in our society

00:01:21.880 --> 00:01:22.880 align:middle line:10%
in the last few decades.

00:01:22.880 --> 00:01:26.890 align:middle line:10%
I think there is a conversation
around prestige around money

00:01:26.890 --> 00:01:29.277 align:middle line:10%
that is perhaps inappropriate.

00:01:29.277 --> 00:01:31.360 align:middle line:10%
But that doesn't mean that
the larger conversation

00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:32.120 align:middle line:10%
is inappropriate.

00:01:32.120 --> 00:01:33.480 align:middle line:10%
We all have to make a living.

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:36.420 align:middle line:10%
I also think for
men, when it comes

00:01:36.420 --> 00:01:39.970 align:middle line:10%
to losing a job,
losing all their money,

00:01:39.970 --> 00:01:41.690 align:middle line:10%
which you really
see in a recession

00:01:41.690 --> 00:01:43.834 align:middle line:10%
or a slow economic
recovery like now,

00:01:43.834 --> 00:01:45.250 align:middle line:10%
I think that there's
actually more

00:01:45.250 --> 00:01:47.770 align:middle line:10%
of a psychic crisis for men
than there is for women.

00:01:47.770 --> 00:01:50.900 align:middle line:84%
And I think women need to
probably appreciate that more.

00:01:50.900 --> 00:01:53.289 align:middle line:84%
A lot of self-worth
based on production.

00:01:53.289 --> 00:01:54.080 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

00:01:54.080 --> 00:01:55.770 align:middle line:84%
>>WILLIAMSON: And that's
a very serious topic.

00:01:55.770 --> 00:01:56.620 align:middle line:90%
It's not nothing.

00:01:56.620 --> 00:01:57.310 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: No, no.

00:01:57.310 --> 00:01:58.768 align:middle line:10%
I'm really glad
you mentioned that,

00:01:58.768 --> 00:02:02.230 align:middle line:10%
because men have a certain
identity that women don't

00:02:02.230 --> 00:02:05.120 align:middle line:10%
usually have that are
gaining more and more,

00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:06.930 align:middle line:10%
but in a healthier
way, hopefully,

00:02:06.930 --> 00:02:09.400 align:middle line:10%
which is why you have
a book like this.

00:02:09.400 --> 00:02:12.130 align:middle line:10%
I have to ask you though about
the economic conversation.

00:02:12.130 --> 00:02:16.520 align:middle line:10%
And in the last decade, it
has been so intensified,

00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:19.985 align:middle line:10%
even in the last couple of
years about the 99% and the 1%.

00:02:19.985 --> 00:02:22.110 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there's so much
focus on this conversation.

00:02:22.110 --> 00:02:24.401 align:middle line:84%
>>WILLIAMSON: Well, it's an
appropriate focus actually.

00:02:24.401 --> 00:02:26.610 align:middle line:84%
What was really not very
healthy in the society

00:02:26.610 --> 00:02:28.710 align:middle line:84%
was that we were not
talking about it.

00:02:28.710 --> 00:02:32.770 align:middle line:10%
Because for several decades we
have been through tax policies

00:02:32.770 --> 00:02:34.360 align:middle line:10%
and through subsidies,
particularly

00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:37.232 align:middle line:10%
to large corporations,
we have followed

00:02:37.232 --> 00:02:39.690 align:middle line:10%
a line of development that's
been going on for quite awhile

00:02:39.690 --> 00:02:43.570 align:middle line:10%
now in which vast amounts
of material resource

00:02:43.570 --> 00:02:46.970 align:middle line:10%
of the country has been siphoned
into the hands of a relatively

00:02:46.970 --> 00:02:47.940 align:middle line:10%
very few.

00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:50.590 align:middle line:10%
And this has not only
created a crisis because

00:02:50.590 --> 00:02:55.500 align:middle line:10%
of the huge economic disparity
between that 1% and everyone

00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:59.170 align:middle line:10%
else, but it's also a
threat to democracy itself.

00:02:59.170 --> 00:03:03.460 align:middle line:10%
You know, the late Supreme
Court Justice, Louis Brandeis,

00:03:03.460 --> 00:03:06.250 align:middle line:10%
said you can either have large
amounts of money concentrated

00:03:06.250 --> 00:03:10.110 align:middle line:10%
in the hands of the very few,
or you can have democracy.

00:03:10.110 --> 00:03:11.760 align:middle line:10%
You cannot have both.

00:03:11.760 --> 00:03:14.370 align:middle line:10%
And there was something else
that went along with this.

00:03:14.370 --> 00:03:16.710 align:middle line:10%
Not only was it an
economic theory,

00:03:16.710 --> 00:03:19.630 align:middle line:10%
the whole idea that if you gave
more money, if you allowed more

00:03:19.630 --> 00:03:23.530 align:middle line:10%
money through reduced taxation
and so forth in the hands

00:03:23.530 --> 00:03:26.400 align:middle line:10%
of a very few, they would be
the so-called job creators.

00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:28.720 align:middle line:10%
Now, first of all,
this-- there's

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:31.790 align:middle line:10%
no evidence that this
is actually ever worked.

00:03:31.790 --> 00:03:34.395 align:middle line:10%
But ideologically,
some of the people,

00:03:34.395 --> 00:03:36.020 align:middle line:10%
particularly like
during the Reagan era

00:03:36.020 --> 00:03:40.220 align:middle line:10%
who instigated that
kind of policy,

00:03:40.220 --> 00:03:43.750 align:middle line:10%
certainly were righteous people
who thought it was a good way

00:03:43.750 --> 00:03:44.810 align:middle line:10%
to stimulate the economy.

00:03:44.810 --> 00:03:46.310 align:middle line:10%
There were a lot
of not particularly

00:03:46.310 --> 00:03:48.300 align:middle line:10%
intended consequences to that.

00:03:48.300 --> 00:03:50.810 align:middle line:10%
But actually, even before that
there was an economist named,

00:03:50.810 --> 00:03:54.350 align:middle line:10%
Milton Friedman, and what
began to happen in the 1970s

00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:57.780 align:middle line:10%
is that we began--
companies began

00:03:57.780 --> 00:04:01.380 align:middle line:10%
to shift their sense of what
their responsibility was

00:04:01.380 --> 00:04:03.720 align:middle line:10%
towards its workers
and their community.

00:04:03.720 --> 00:04:07.650 align:middle line:10%
And this issue of what's
called shareholder value

00:04:07.650 --> 00:04:08.750 align:middle line:10%
became in vogue.

00:04:08.750 --> 00:04:10.780 align:middle line:10%
Now what that means
has very interesting

00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:13.880 align:middle line:10%
psychological and
philosophical implications,

00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:16.240 align:middle line:10%
because what they basically
said was that instead

00:04:16.240 --> 00:04:18.010 align:middle line:10%
of a company making
its business,

00:04:18.010 --> 00:04:20.869 align:middle line:10%
let's say that it make the
best computer in the world.

00:04:20.869 --> 00:04:22.910 align:middle line:10%
And then, what it would
be about with its workers

00:04:22.910 --> 00:04:25.000 align:middle line:10%
is we're going to make the
best-- I don't know if it was

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.624 align:middle line:10%
at that time a computer, because
computers were just starting--

00:04:27.624 --> 00:04:30.310 align:middle line:10%
but we're going to make the
best machine in the world.

00:04:30.310 --> 00:04:32.580 align:middle line:10%
And then you had this
relationship with your workers.

00:04:32.580 --> 00:04:34.730 align:middle line:84%
You working together to
make the best machine.

00:04:34.730 --> 00:04:34.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:04:34.920 --> 00:04:35.420 align:middle line:90%
A team.

00:04:35.420 --> 00:04:36.920 align:middle line:84%
>>WILLIAMSON: You
had a relationship

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:40.340 align:middle line:84%
with your clients
that best-- OK.

00:04:40.340 --> 00:04:43.030 align:middle line:10%
When this shareholder
value became in vogue,

00:04:43.030 --> 00:04:45.880 align:middle line:10%
this was the idea
that no, no, no,

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:48.650 align:middle line:10%
the most important thing is not
that you make the best machine.

00:04:48.650 --> 00:04:50.150 align:middle line:10%
The most important
thing is that you

00:04:50.150 --> 00:04:52.930 align:middle line:10%
make money for the
shareholders in the company.

00:04:52.930 --> 00:04:54.942 align:middle line:10%
Now the idea, you could
see the value of it.

00:04:54.942 --> 00:04:57.150 align:middle line:10%
In other words, the company
makes a machine and goes,

00:04:57.150 --> 00:05:00.340 align:middle line:10%
well, if our bottom
line is to make money

00:05:00.340 --> 00:05:02.279 align:middle line:10%
for the shareholders,
then we're not only

00:05:02.279 --> 00:05:04.820 align:middle line:10%
thinking about making the best
machine, we're thinking, well,

00:05:04.820 --> 00:05:07.420 align:middle line:10%
maybe we'll also
manufacture the widget

00:05:07.420 --> 00:05:08.770 align:middle line:10%
that will go with the machine.

00:05:08.770 --> 00:05:11.080 align:middle line:84%
However, look from a
philosophical and spiritual

00:05:11.080 --> 00:05:12.470 align:middle line:90%
basis what this did.

00:05:12.470 --> 00:05:14.400 align:middle line:84%
It threw the
universe off in terms

00:05:14.400 --> 00:05:17.620 align:middle line:84%
of the relationship between
the company and its workers.

00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:19.620 align:middle line:10%
Because instead of saying
we're working together

00:05:19.620 --> 00:05:21.620 align:middle line:10%
to make the best
machine, we're saying

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:24.100 align:middle line:10%
we need your wages to
go down, because we

00:05:24.100 --> 00:05:27.277 align:middle line:10%
need to create more money
for the shareholders.

00:05:27.277 --> 00:05:28.610 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Or you'll lose your job.

00:05:28.610 --> 00:05:31.235 align:middle line:10%
>>WILLIAMSON: Yes, well, that's
when it's taken to the extreme,

00:05:31.235 --> 00:05:31.800 align:middle line:10%
absolutely.

00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:33.910 align:middle line:10%
So it threw off the
relationship, the righteous.

00:05:33.910 --> 00:05:36.672 align:middle line:10%
It threw off the universe
between the company

00:05:36.672 --> 00:05:38.880 align:middle line:10%
and its workers, between
the company and its clients.

00:05:38.880 --> 00:05:40.830 align:middle line:10%
And when taken to the
extreme, of course,

00:05:40.830 --> 00:05:42.350 align:middle line:10%
between the company
and the Earth,

00:05:42.350 --> 00:05:45.006 align:middle line:10%
because anything that
has to be hurt in order

00:05:45.006 --> 00:05:46.880 align:middle line:10%
to increase that bottom
line to shareholders,

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:48.650 align:middle line:10%
and that began about the 1970s.

00:05:48.650 --> 00:05:52.830 align:middle line:10%
And it is thrown off
the moral universe.

00:05:52.830 --> 00:05:55.580 align:middle line:10%
When it comes to the
spiritual conversation,

00:05:55.580 --> 00:05:59.140 align:middle line:10%
that ethical center,
that issue that all

00:05:59.140 --> 00:06:00.830 align:middle line:10%
is to be right
with the universe,

00:06:00.830 --> 00:06:03.810 align:middle line:10%
that we are righteous,
right use of the mind.

00:06:03.810 --> 00:06:07.310 align:middle line:84%
Not only with a divine
creator, some higher

00:06:07.310 --> 00:06:10.440 align:middle line:84%
power with the universe
itself, with each other,

00:06:10.440 --> 00:06:12.450 align:middle line:84%
with our own hearts, and
our sense of integrity,

00:06:12.450 --> 00:06:14.020 align:middle line:90%
and with the Earth itself.

00:06:14.020 --> 00:06:16.530 align:middle line:10%
You mess with that and
nothing is ultimately

00:06:16.530 --> 00:06:18.434 align:middle line:10%
going to work
either in the house

00:06:18.434 --> 00:06:20.350 align:middle line:10%
in the life of the
individual or in the larger

00:06:20.350 --> 00:06:21.270 align:middle line:10%
economic picture for anybody.

00:06:21.270 --> 00:06:23.353 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It throws a cog
in the whole entire wheel.

00:06:23.353 --> 00:06:24.650 align:middle line:90%
>>WILLIAMSON: Absolutely.

00:06:24.650 --> 00:06:27.180 align:middle line:84%
Because it made money more
important than people,

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:28.940 align:middle line:84%
more important than
life, more important--

00:06:28.940 --> 00:06:30.380 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Which is what
we're feeling now.

00:06:30.380 --> 00:06:32.120 align:middle line:84%
>>WILLIAMSON: We're
experiencing it big time now.

00:06:32.120 --> 00:06:33.840 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Losing jobs,
being laid off,

00:06:33.840 --> 00:06:37.720 align:middle line:10%
taking hits and cuts in pay
so that we could have jobs.

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:40.690 align:middle line:10%
And so, say you are one of those
people, and you're watching,

00:06:40.690 --> 00:06:42.810 align:middle line:10%
and you've been applying
for a job for two,

00:06:42.810 --> 00:06:45.640 align:middle line:10%
three years and not
able to find anything.

00:06:45.640 --> 00:06:49.190 align:middle line:10%
So what can we
shift in ourselves

00:06:49.190 --> 00:06:50.690 align:middle line:10%
to turn that
conversation around?

00:06:50.690 --> 00:06:52.314 align:middle line:10%
We know it's happening
in the exterior,

00:06:52.314 --> 00:06:54.530 align:middle line:10%
and so that we don't
become victims to that.

00:06:54.530 --> 00:06:57.197 align:middle line:10%
>>WILLIAMSON: OK, well, first of
all it's not quite so separate,

00:06:57.197 --> 00:06:58.696 align:middle line:10%
because then I think
a lot of people

00:06:58.696 --> 00:07:00.440 align:middle line:10%
in the new thought,
new spirituality,

00:07:00.440 --> 00:07:03.054 align:middle line:10%
thinks that, well, what about
only in my individual life?

00:07:03.054 --> 00:07:04.720 align:middle line:10%
I think people are
waking up to the fact

00:07:04.720 --> 00:07:06.830 align:middle line:10%
that we do not
live in isolation.

00:07:06.830 --> 00:07:09.970 align:middle line:10%
And I think that the economic
crisis that has hit our society

00:07:09.970 --> 00:07:11.650 align:middle line:10%
has certainly made
that clear to people.

00:07:11.650 --> 00:07:12.787 align:middle line:10%
It's not just about you.

00:07:12.787 --> 00:07:13.870 align:middle line:10%
It's about the collective.

00:07:13.870 --> 00:07:16.550 align:middle line:10%
And a lot of the forces,
social and economic,

00:07:16.550 --> 00:07:19.850 align:middle line:10%
that affect the whole society
come home and hit you.

00:07:19.850 --> 00:07:22.810 align:middle line:10%
So that alone should
awaken all of us

00:07:22.810 --> 00:07:25.411 align:middle line:10%
from this sort of personally
isolationist stupor.

00:07:25.411 --> 00:07:27.410 align:middle line:10%
Well, I don't have anything
to do with politics.

00:07:27.410 --> 00:07:29.210 align:middle line:10%
I don't have anything
to do with that stuff.

00:07:29.210 --> 00:07:30.570 align:middle line:90%
I'm just trying to live my life.

00:07:30.570 --> 00:07:33.064 align:middle line:84%
Well, let me tell you, it's
going to come home to you.

00:07:33.064 --> 00:07:34.980 align:middle line:84%
Like the French say, if
you don't do politics,

00:07:34.980 --> 00:07:36.320 align:middle line:90%
politics will do you.

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:38.860 align:middle line:84%
So what this book is about
is about the personal,

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:40.850 align:middle line:84%
which is called
the microeconomic.

00:07:40.850 --> 00:07:42.810 align:middle line:10%
It's about the personal
relationship to money

00:07:42.810 --> 00:07:45.410 align:middle line:10%
and what you were saying,
what does one individual do?

00:07:45.410 --> 00:07:48.320 align:middle line:10%
Well, this is what, not only
the "Course of Miracles,"

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:53.430 align:middle line:10%
but any metaphysical treatise
or teaching basically says.

00:07:53.430 --> 00:07:55.600 align:middle line:10%
It is a self-organizing
universe,

00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:57.850 align:middle line:10%
and these are the two
principles that guide this book.

00:07:57.850 --> 00:07:59.870 align:middle line:10%
It is a self-organizing
universe,

00:07:59.870 --> 00:08:02.760 align:middle line:10%
and it is a
self-correcting universe.

00:08:02.760 --> 00:08:05.870 align:middle line:10%
Now, number one,
self-organizing, the embryo

00:08:05.870 --> 00:08:07.279 align:middle line:10%
knows how to turn into a baby.

00:08:07.279 --> 00:08:07.820 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: True.

00:08:07.820 --> 00:08:10.650 align:middle line:10%
>>WILLIAMSON: The acorn knows
how to turn into an oak tree.

00:08:10.650 --> 00:08:12.860 align:middle line:10%
The bud knows how to
turn into a blossom.

00:08:12.860 --> 00:08:13.360 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: OK.

00:08:13.360 --> 00:08:15.290 align:middle line:10%
>>WILLIAMSON: Within
nature, it is obvious

00:08:15.290 --> 00:08:17.620 align:middle line:10%
that there is a natural
intelligence at work.

00:08:17.620 --> 00:08:18.889 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: A self-organizing--

00:08:18.889 --> 00:08:19.930 align:middle line:90%
>>WILLIAMSON: Absolutely.

00:08:19.930 --> 00:08:21.520 align:middle line:90%
The cells know how to divide.

00:08:21.520 --> 00:08:24.810 align:middle line:10%
Now, it's not like-- We
seem to act, at least,

00:08:24.810 --> 00:08:28.554 align:middle line:10%
or we certainly seem to think
that all these little cells

00:08:28.554 --> 00:08:29.970 align:middle line:10%
came together and
knew how to form

00:08:29.970 --> 00:08:33.419 align:middle line:10%
a brain, and eyes, and skin,
and all this amazing stuff

00:08:33.419 --> 00:08:36.090 align:middle line:10%
of your body, but then we live
as though then you were born

00:08:36.090 --> 00:08:37.850 align:middle line:10%
and you're on your own.

00:08:37.850 --> 00:08:41.179 align:middle line:10%
But the spiritual
perspective is that not only

00:08:41.179 --> 00:08:43.480 align:middle line:10%
